    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. so if i see a massive spike in neutrophils specifically, what kind of cellular mechanisms are actually driving that? like what is happening at the bone marrow level to cause a sudden surge like that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A sudden, massive spike in neutrophils, known as a neutrophilia, is driven by the bone marrow rapidly accelerating the production and release of these cells. This is often stimulated by inflammatory cytokines, such as granulocyte colony-stimulating factor (G-CSF), which tells the bone marrow to pump out mature neutrophils faster. Furthermore, the body can release stored neutrophils from the bloodstream into the tissue environment, contributing to the increased count. This massive mobilization is the body's rapid defense against an acute threat.",
      "source": "target",
