    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "could u elaborate on the \"rapid mobilization\" part? u mentioned they are released into the tissue environment to deal with threats. what does that process actually look like on a microscopic level when the cells are moving toward the site of injury?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When neutrophils are moving toward an injury site, a process called **chemotaxis** is occurring. Inflammatory mediators released at the site, like chemokines, act as chemical beacons, attracting the neutrophils. Microscopically, these cells adhere to the endothelial lining of the blood vessels, a process called **margination** and **rolling**. They then squeeze between the endothelial cells in a process called **diapedesis** to enter the tissue and begin phagocytizing the invading pathogens.",
      "source": "target",
